{"parse":{"title":"Study mama","pageid":6039529,"revid":844418425,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p><b>P\u00e9id\u00fa m\u0101m\u0101</b> (\u966a\u8bfb\u5988\u5988), or <b>study mamas</b> are foreign women who accompany their children to <a href=\"/wiki/Singapore\" title=\"Singapore\">Singapore</a> while their children receive primary and secondary-level education. The study mama phenomenon began in 2000, after the Singapore Government relaxed its immigration policies to attract more foreigners. Most of the study mamas are from <a href=\"/wiki/Mainland_China\" title=\"Mainland China\">mainland China</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-stw_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-stw-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Introduction\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Introduction</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Jobs\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Jobs</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#Government\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Government</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#Incidents\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Incidents</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-5\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">5</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Introduction\">Introduction</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Study_mama&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Introduction\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The Immigration and Checkpoints Authority of Singapore possesses records that suggest that there are at least 7,800 study mamas of various nationalities, with two-thirds of the 6,800 study mamas in Singapore in July 2005 coming from China. Of these 6,800 study mamas, only 1,000 have been issued work permits.<sup id=\"cite_ref-stw_1-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-stw-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> Most working study mamas are employed in the service sector.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Jobs\">Jobs</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Study_mama&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Jobs\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>In an article in <i><a href=\"/wiki/People%27s_Daily\" title=\"People&#39;s Daily\">People's Daily</a></i>, it is estimated that peidu mamas require <a href=\"/wiki/RMB\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"RMB\">RMB</a>\u00a51 million (approx <a href=\"/wiki/S$\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"S$\">S$</a>217,000) of living and education expenses for their child to receive education from Primary 1 to Secondary 4 in Singapore.<sup id=\"cite_ref-pc_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-pc-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> \nThe Singapore Government allowed them to come to Singapore, primarily to accompany their children during their studies here.<sup id=\"cite_ref-stw_1-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-stw-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> Peidu mamas are only allowed to obtain work permits after staying in Singapore for a year and are permitted to work in certain service sectors only.<sup id=\"cite_ref-to_3-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-to-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Government\">Government</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Study_mama&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Government\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The government places restriction on the employment of study mamas, arguing that their primary purpose of stay here is to take care of their children. Hence they should not be working, especially not as <a href=\"/wiki/Hostess_bar\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Hostess bar\">hostesses</a> in bars or <a href=\"/wiki/Pub\" title=\"Pub\">pubs</a> at night. They are not allowed to work at food stalls, but can work in other services industries if given permits.<sup id=\"cite_ref-stw_1-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-stw-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Incidents\">Incidents</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Study_mama&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: Incidents\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>In October 2004, the daughter of a study mama, <a href=\"/wiki/Huang_Na\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Huang Na\">Huang Na</a> went missing and was subsequently found murdered.\n</p><p>In June 2006, a female Chinese national who owned a <a href=\"/wiki/Massage_parlour\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Massage parlour\">massage parlour</a>, which allegedly provided sex services to clients, was stabbed to death in <a href=\"/wiki/Ang_Mo_Kio\" title=\"Ang Mo Kio\">Ang Mo Kio</a>. This drew public and media attention to vice-related activities at some of these massage parlours. In early July 2006, the government conducted a crackdown on illegal employment at the parlours and imposed stricter regulation on their operations. This led some peidu mamas to hold a protest outside the Chinese <a href=\"/wiki/Embassy\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Embassy\">Embassy</a>, despite the prohibition of such gatherings in Singapore.<sup id=\"cite_ref-to_3-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-to-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Study_mama&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-stw-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-stw_1-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-stw_1-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-stw_1-2\"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-stw_1-3\"><sup><i><b>d</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation news\">\"Who owes them a living?\". <a href=\"/wiki/The_Straits_Times\" title=\"The Straits Times\">The Straits Times</a>. 2006-07-09.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.atitle=Who+owes+them+a+living%3F&amp;rft.date=2006-07-09&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AStudy+mama\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-pc-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-pc_2-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation news\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://web.archive.org/web/20060717192424/http://www.pconline.com.cn/pcjob/language/info/10311/248244.html\">\"\u65b0\u52a0\u5761:\u4e2d\u56fd\"\u966a\u8bfb\u5988\u5988\"\u82e6\u6c34\u591a\"</a>. Archived from <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.pconline.com.cn/pcjob/language/info/10311/248244.html\">the original</a> on 2006-07-17.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.atitle=%E6%96%B0%E5%8A%A0%E5%9D%A1%3A%E4%B8%AD%E5%9B%BD%22%E9%99%AA%E8%AF%BB%E5%A6%88%E5%A6%88%22%E8%8B%A6%E6%B0%B4%E5%A4%9A&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.pconline.com.cn%2Fpcjob%2Flanguage%2Finfo%2F10311%2F248244.html&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AStudy+mama\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-to-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-to_3-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-to_3-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation news\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://web.archive.org/web/20070311164815/http://www.todayonline.com/articles/129342.asp\">\"Study mamas in embassy protest\"</a>. <a href=\"/wiki/TODAYOnline\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"TODAYOnline\">TODAYOnline</a>. 2006-07-08. Archived from <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.todayonline.com/articles/129342.asp\">the original</a> on 2007-03-11.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.atitle=Study+mamas+in+embassy+protest&amp;rft.date=2006-07-08&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.todayonline.com%2Farticles%2F129342.asp&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AStudy+mama\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n</ol></div>\n\n<!-- \nNewPP limit report\nParsed by mw1254\nCached time: 20180908055117\nCache expiry: 1900800\nDynamic content: false\nCPU time usage: 0.052 seconds\nReal time usage: 0.070 seconds\nPreprocessor visited node count: 146/1000000\nPreprocessor generated node count: 0/1500000\nPost\u2010expand include size: 3434/2097152 bytes\nTemplate argument size: 0/2097152 bytes\nHighest expansion depth: 3/40\nExpensive parser function count: 0/500\nUnstrip recursion depth: 0/20\nUnst